2026-04-21 01:31:49 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control (ambient sensor) module relay driver / comparator output-stage coupling to relay coil'] hypothesis_explanation='All tested passive components, potentiometers, light‑sensor subcircuit, supply rails, and relay contacts themselves behave nominally, yet the control module is repeatedly reported to be in an unstable/oscillating state while the system is powered. The lamp intermittently turns off, but the relay contact and coil continuity are normal and supply polarity is correct.\n\nThis points to a fault in the active output stage that drives the relay coil from the comparator/op‑amp output, or in the immediate coupling between the comparator output and the relay coil. A marginal, partially shorted, or leaky transistor/driver device, or an incorrect/unstable feedback path at this stage, can repeatedly pull the comparator into oscillation on a long time constant without appearing as a simple open or short in DC continuity tests. This would explain:\n- Persistent reports of an ‘unstable/oscillating state’ in the control module even when the lamp appears steady under some knob settings.\n- Normal sensor and timing network measurements, with correct high/low logic levels available on the supply rails.\n- Intermittent lamp dropouts, since the relay coil is being momentarily released or its drive is collapsing despite healthy upstream circuitry and contacts.\n\nTherefore I hypothesize that the specific fault resides in the relay driver / comparator output-stage portion of the control (ambient sensor) module rather than in the timing network, sensor, or relay contacts themselves.'
